import{_ as t,o,c as a,ao as n}from"./chunks/framework.kY99y3RA.js";const g=JSON.parse('{"title":"The Codelet Generator (genfft analogue) — Knowledge Base","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"codelet-generator.md","filePath":"codelet-generator.md","lastUpdated":null}'),r={name:"codelet-generator.md"};function s(i,e,l,d,c,h){return o(),a("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[n('<h1 id="The-Codelet-Generator-genfft-analogue-—-Knowledge-Base" tabindex="-1">The Codelet Generator (genfft analogue) — Knowledge Base <a class="header-anchor" href="#The-Codelet-Generator-genfft-analogue-—-Knowledge-Base" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The Codelet Generator (genfft analogue) — Knowledge Base {#The-Codelet-Generator-genfft-analogue-—-Knowledge-Base}&quot;">​</a></h1><p>This is the reference knowledge base for PureFFT&#39;s <strong>Julia-native FFT codelet generator</strong> — the analogue of FFTW&#39;s <code>genfft</code>. It captures the literature on how genfft works, the SIMD-vectorization theory, and how both map onto PureFFT&#39;s existing infrastructure, so the design and implementation can refer to it without re-deriving. The architecture + PoC plan that consumes this KB lives in the plan file (<code>docs/superpowers/plans/…</code> / the approved plan); this page is the <em>background</em>, not the plan.</p><blockquote><p><strong>Constraint: we cannot read FFTW&#39;s source.</strong> Everything here is from the published papers, the Burrus textbook, and FFTW.jl&#39;s bindings — never FFTW&#39;s C/OCaml source. Sources are listed at the bottom.</p></blockquote><h2 id="Why-a-codelet-generator-the-Julia-only-advantage" tabindex="-1">Why a codelet generator (the Julia-only advantage) <a class="header-anchor" href="#Why-a-codelet-generator-the-Julia-only-advantage" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Why a codelet generator (the Julia-only advantage) {#Why-a-codelet-generator-the-Julia-only-advantage}&quot;">​</a></h2><p>FFTW is fast because its small fixed-size FFT kernels (&quot;codelets&quot;) are <em>generated</em> by a program (<code>genfft</code>) that applies FFT-specific optimizations a general compiler does not. But genfft runs <strong>once, at FFTW build time</strong>, and the codelets are compiled into the library; RustFFT similarly fixes its kernels at compile time. <strong>Neither can synthesize a new optimized kernel for a size it did not anticipate</strong> — they fall back to slower general routines.</p><p>Julia can: <code>@generated</code> functions (and runtime <code>eval</code>) specialize code <strong>per size, on first use</strong>. PureFFT already exploits a limited form of this. A full generator would give <strong>optimized codelets for any size on demand</strong> — a capability that is structurally impossible for an ahead-of-time C/Rust library, and the clearest reason a from-scratch Julia FFT can be more than &quot;FFTW re-implemented.&quot;</p><h2 id="genfft-—-the-four-phases" tabindex="-1">genfft — the four phases <a class="header-anchor" href="#genfft-—-the-four-phases" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;genfft — the four phases {#genfft-—-the-four-phases}&quot;">​</a></h2><p>genfft (FFTW&#39;s generator, written in OCaml) compiles a size-<code>n</code> DFT into a straight-line codelet in four phases:</p><h3 id="1.-Creation" tabindex="-1">1. Creation <a class="header-anchor" href="#1.-Creation" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;1. Creation {#1.-Creation}&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Build a <strong>directed acyclic graph (DAG)</strong> of complex operations (<code>+</code>, <code>−</code>, <code>×constant</code>) by evaluating a DFT algorithm <em>symbolically</em> — &quot;expressed in a straightforward math-like notation, using complex numbers, with no attempt at optimization.&quot; The algorithm is chosen per size:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Cooley–Tukey</strong> (<code>n = n₁·n₂</code>, the general recursive factorization),</p></li><li><p><strong>split-radix</strong> (the lowest known operation count for powers of two),</p></li><li><p><strong>prime-factor / Good–Thomas</strong> (coprime factors, no twiddles between stages),</p></li><li><p><strong>Rader</strong> (a prime <code>p</code> as a length-<code>p−1</code> cyclic convolution).</p></li></ul><p>The output is a linear network where edges carry multiplicative constants and vertices perform additions.</p><h3 id="2.-Simplification" tabindex="-1">2. Simplification <a class="header-anchor" href="#2.-Simplification" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;2. Simplification {#2.-Simplification}&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Local rewrite rules applied to every DAG node, plus global passes. This is where genfft earns most of its advantage over naively-emitted code:</p><ul><li><p><strong>Algebraic simplification / constant folding:</strong> eliminate <code>×0</code>, <code>×1</code>, <code>×−1</code>, and the special rotations <code>×±i</code> (which are lane swaps + sign flips, not multiplies); fold <code>constant × constant</code>.</p></li><li><p><strong>Sign propagation:</strong> &quot;make all the numeric constants positive and propagate the minus sign along the edges of the DAG&quot; — turning additions into subtractions (or vice versa) elsewhere. Reported <strong>10–15% speedup</strong>. (Fewer distinct constants → more CSE hits and simpler immediates.)</p></li><li><p><strong>Common-subexpression elimination (CSE):</strong> hash-cons identical subgraphs so each is computed once. This is the single largest op-count reducer — and the one a modern backend compiler is <em>also</em> likely to do (see &quot;the make-or-break question&quot;).</p></li><li><p><strong>Network transposition:</strong> reverse the direction of every edge in the DAG, run CSE again, then transpose back. By the network-transposition theorem the transposed graph computes the transposed linear map; CSE on it exposes common subexpressions that a single forward pass misses. A genfft-specific trick.</p></li><li><p><strong>Real-data specialization:</strong> automatically prune the complex DAG to derive real-input (r2c / r2r) algorithms at near-minimal operation count.</p></li></ul><h3 id="3.-Scheduling" tabindex="-1">3. Scheduling <a class="header-anchor" href="#3.-Scheduling" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;3. Scheduling {#3.-Scheduling}&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Produce a <strong>topological sort</strong> of the simplified DAG — an order of operations — chosen so the backend compiler can register-allocate well. genfft&#39;s scheduler is <strong>cache-oblivious</strong>, treating the register file as a cache: it recursively partitions the DAG to keep the working set (live values) small, which bounds register pressure / spills. The theory connects to cache-oblivious algorithms and the red–blue pebble game. &quot;One consequence of this scheduler is that FFTW&#39;s machine-independent codelets are no slower than machine-specific codelets generated by SPIRAL.&quot;</p><h3 id="4.-Unparse" tabindex="-1">4. Unparse <a class="header-anchor" href="#4.-Unparse" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;4. Unparse {#4.-Unparse}&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Emit the scheduled DAG as <strong>straight-line code</strong> (C in stock genfft; assembly optionally). Two flavors:</p><ul><li><p><strong>No-twiddle codelet:</strong> a plain size-<code>n</code> DFT (used as a leaf / base case).</p></li><li><p><strong>Twiddle codelet:</strong> inputs/outputs are pre/post-multiplied by twiddle factors, so the codelet drops directly into a Cooley–Tukey step. Codelet sizes are typically <code>n ≤ 64</code>. The planner composes these codelets (timing combinations) into a plan for the full transform.</p></li></ul><h2 id="SIMD:-vectorize-straight-line-blocks,-not-loops" tabindex="-1">SIMD: vectorize straight-line blocks, not loops <a class="header-anchor" href="#SIMD:-vectorize-straight-line-blocks,-not-loops" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;SIMD: vectorize straight-line blocks, not loops {#SIMD:-vectorize-straight-line-blocks,-not-loops}&quot;">​</a></h2><p>A general loop-vectorizing compiler cannot vectorize FFTW: the strides are runtime-determined and most codelets have <em>no loops</em> (they are straight-line blocks). FFTW instead <strong>vectorizes the straight-line code itself</strong>, with SIMD lanes holding <strong>independent sub-transforms</strong> (the &quot;vector rank&quot; / batch dimension). The data layout is split (separate real/imaginary streams) so the arithmetic is plain FMA chains with <strong>no intra-transform shuffles or transposes</strong>.</p><p>This is the key fact for PureFFT: it is the <strong>batch-vectorization axis</strong>, and it is <em>transpose-free</em>. It contrasts with column-packing (packing several columns of one transform into a SIMD register), which incurs intra-transform transpose shuffles. PureFFT&#39;s measured non-pow2 floors (e.g. <code>2^a·5³</code>) were root-caused to exactly this — FFTW vectorizes across the batch, PureFFT column-packs. The canonical reference for how to vectorize straight-line FFT code is Franchetti et al. (see sources).</p><h2 id="How-this-maps-onto-PureFFT-existing-seeds-the-gap" tabindex="-1">How this maps onto PureFFT (existing seeds + the gap) <a class="header-anchor" href="#How-this-maps-onto-PureFFT-existing-seeds-the-gap" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;How this maps onto PureFFT (existing seeds + the gap) {#How-this-maps-onto-PureFFT-existing-seeds-the-gap}&quot;">​</a></h2><p>PureFFT is <strong>not greenfield</strong> here:</p><ul><li><p><strong><code>src/codelets.jl</code> is a working genfft seed.</strong> Its four generators (<code>_gen_dft!</code>, <code>_gen_dft_mixed!</code>, <code>_gen_dft_soa!</code>, <code>_gen_dft_soa_mixed!</code>) build straight-line DFT code at <code>@generated</code>-dispatch time with baked twiddle constants and Cooley–Tukey mixed-radix recursion, for <strong>any size</strong> — a complete <em>Creation</em> phase plus a sliver of <em>Simplification</em> (it already elides <code>×1</code> and <code>×±i</code>). It powers <code>CodeletPlan</code>, <code>FourStepCodeletPlan</code>, and <code>RecursiveMixedRadixPlan</code>.</p></li><li><p><strong>The batch-vectorization axis already exists in seed form.</strong> <code>_dft_codelet_soa_batched!</code> / <code>_dft_codelet_soa_batched_tw!</code> emit a <code>Vec{W,T}</code> body vectorizing across <code>W</code> <em>independent</em> transforms (split re/im, no intra-transform shuffles) — FFTW&#39;s transpose-free strategy. <code>FourStepCodeletPlan</code> drives two such passes for a four-step <code>n = n₁·n₂</code>.</p></li><li><p><strong>What&#39;s missing is exactly genfft&#39;s optimization layer:</strong> there is no explicit IR, no CSE, no sign-propagation, no scheduling, no network-transposition. The generators emit the naive DAG and rely on LLVM.</p></li><li><p><strong>The <code>src/avxradix/</code> SIMD layer is the hand-written, per-size &quot;ad-hoc&quot; part</strong> (~50 functions across two register widths; a new radix touches ~6 places). <code>avx_colbf_prime</code> (a <code>@generated</code> width-generic prime butterfly) is its only generative element. Systematizing this layer is the generator&#39;s long-term goal.</p></li></ul><p>So the generator is built by inserting an <strong>explicit IR + a few optimization passes</strong> between the existing frontends and backends, and promoting the batched backend to first-class.</p><h2 id="The-make-or-break-question:-does-this-beat-modern-LLVM?" tabindex="-1">The make-or-break question: does this beat modern LLVM? <a class="header-anchor" href="#The-make-or-break-question:-does-this-beat-modern-LLVM?" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The make-or-break question: does this beat modern LLVM? {#The-make-or-break-question:-does-this-beat-modern-LLVM?}&quot;">​</a></h2><p>genfft&#39;s advantage was measured against 1990s C compilers. Modern <strong>LLVM already performs aggressive CSE, instruction scheduling, and register allocation.</strong> PureFFT&#39;s own <code>julia-sched-mwe/</code> reproducer found that <strong>LLVM compiles our radix-9/12 DAGs to asm at least as fast as Rust&#39;s</strong> — i.e. the classic genfft &quot;schedules better than the compiler&quot; edge may be <em>narrow</em> against LLVM 18+.</p><p>Therefore the implementation must, <strong>before building any compiler</strong>, measure (via <code>@code_native</code> instruction-count diffs on a real codelet) whether each genfft pass actually changes what LLVM emits. A pass LLVM already performs is deleted, not kept &quot;for completeness.&quot; The <em>verified-value</em> layer is batch-vectorization (which mostly already exists and addresses a measured floor); the scalar CSE/schedule passes are the high-risk, possibly-redundant layer and are gated by measurement.</p><h2 id="Trim-safety-and-the-generate-time-/-runtime-split" tabindex="-1">Trim-safety and the generate-time / runtime split <a class="header-anchor" href="#Trim-safety-and-the-generate-time-/-runtime-split" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Trim-safety and the generate-time / runtime split {#Trim-safety-and-the-generate-time-/-runtime-split}&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The symbolic DAG/CSE/scheduling work uses dynamic structures (<code>Vector{Any}</code>-style) that must <strong>never appear in the runtime hot path</strong> (PureFFT targets <code>--trim</code> / static compilation; verified via TrimCheck and StrictMode). The resolution mirrors genfft: the generator runs <strong>entirely at generate time</strong> (inside <code>@generated</code> bodies or a precompile build step) and emits <strong>only concrete, straight-line code</strong>. The runtime is the emitted kernel — trim-safe by construction.</p><h2 id="Implementation-lessons-hard-won,-measured" tabindex="-1">Implementation lessons (hard-won, measured) <a class="header-anchor" href="#Implementation-lessons-hard-won,-measured" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Implementation lessons (hard-won, measured) {#Implementation-lessons-hard-won,-measured}&quot;">​</a></h2><p>These cost real debugging on the avxradix systematization (2026-06-30) — heed them when wiring any generated kernel into the hot path.</p><h3 id="A-@generated-kernel-used-in-a-runtime-loop-MUST-be-@inline" tabindex="-1">A <code>@generated</code> kernel used in a runtime loop MUST be <code>@inline</code> <a class="header-anchor" href="#A-@generated-kernel-used-in-a-runtime-loop-MUST-be-@inline" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;A `@generated` kernel used in a runtime loop MUST be `@inline` {#A-@generated-kernel-used-in-a-runtime-loop-MUST-be-@inline}&quot;">​</a></h3><p>A <code>@generated</code> function is <strong>not</strong> inlined by default. When such a kernel is called inside a <em>runtime</em> loop (e.g. a mixed-radix column-pass <code>for c in 0:M÷2-1</code>), the non-inlined form pays, <strong>every iteration</strong>, a call plus tuple-argument passing (packing <code>(r1,…,rP)</code> / the twiddle tuple on the stack). Measured: replacing hand <code>@inline avx_column_butterfly{5,7,13}</code> with the <code>@generated avx_colbf_prime</code> (not marked <code>@inline</code>) regressed the radix-5/7/13 passes to <strong>0.64–0.89× vs hand</strong> — even though the generated body has <strong>identical</strong> op-counts (cb5=25, cb7=43, cb13=121 vector ops). The same generator is fast inside <code>gen_pp_codelet!</code> <em>only because</em> gen_pp forces <code>@inline avx_colbf_prime(...)</code>at its (fully-unrolled, straight-line) call site. Fix:<code>@inline @generated function avx_colbf_prime(...)</code>. After it, several sizes were <em>faster</em> than the hand kernels. <strong>Mark every generated hot-path kernel<code>@inline</code></strong> (or force<code>@inline</code> at the call site).</p><h3 id="Diagnose-generated-vs-hand-regressions-by-op-count-first" tabindex="-1">Diagnose generated-vs-hand regressions by op-count first <a class="header-anchor" href="#Diagnose-generated-vs-hand-regressions-by-op-count-first" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Diagnose generated-vs-hand regressions by op-count first {#Diagnose-generated-vs-hand-regressions-by-op-count-first}&quot;">​</a></h3><p><code>@code_native</code> the kernel <strong>directly</strong> (not through a <code>@noinline</code> wrapper — the wrapper hides the un-inlined call as zero vector ops) and count <code>vfmadd*/vmulpd/vaddpd/vshuf*…</code>. <strong>Identical op-count ⇒ not algorithmic</strong> (no missing CSE) ⇒ the gap is inlining or scheduling; try <code>@inline</code> before anything else. More ops ⇒ the generator is missing a hand simplification.</p><h3 id="Gate-a-generated-replacement-against-the-CURRENT-hand-tuned-kernel,-not-FFTW/RustFFT" tabindex="-1">Gate a generated replacement against the CURRENT hand-tuned kernel, not FFTW/RustFFT <a class="header-anchor" href="#Gate-a-generated-replacement-against-the-CURRENT-hand-tuned-kernel,-not-FFTW/RustFFT" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Gate a generated replacement against the CURRENT hand-tuned kernel, not FFTW/RustFFT {#Gate-a-generated-replacement-against-the-CURRENT-hand-tuned-kernel,-not-FFTW/RustFFT}&quot;">​</a></h3><p>PureFFT&#39;s hand-tuned path now beats FFTW/RustFFT by up to ~6×, so a 0.96×-vs-FFTW gate is far too loose — it would pass a kernel that is a catastrophic regression vs the kernel it replaces. The <strong>binding</strong> gate is par-or-faster (≥0.96×) vs the current hand kernel, pinned (<code>bench/cpufreq_lock.sh pin 4500</code>, <code>taskset -c 2</code>, BenchmarkTools <code>setup=copy</code> median). &quot;Numerically correct vs a reference DFT&quot; and &quot;byte-identical by construction&quot; are <strong>not</strong> substitutes for measuring it — <code>avx_colbf_prime</code> is numerically equivalent (≤2 ULP) but <em>not</em> byte-identical to hand <code>cb5</code>, and was slower until inlined.</p><h3 id="Beware-the-overflow-to-NaN-benchmarking-artifact" tabindex="-1">Beware the overflow-to-NaN benchmarking artifact <a class="header-anchor" href="#Beware-the-overflow-to-NaN-benchmarking-artifact" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Beware the overflow-to-NaN benchmarking artifact {#Beware-the-overflow-to-NaN-benchmarking-artifact}&quot;">​</a></h3><p>Timing repeated <em>in-place</em> <code>pfft!</code> reps without re-seeding lets the FFT magnitude overflow to Inf/NaN within a few iterations → you measure Inf/NaN-arithmetic throughput on garbage, which differs across code structures and produces implausible ratios (e.g. 1.3× &quot;faster&quot;). Use BenchmarkTools <code>setup=copy</code> (fresh data per sample).</p><h2 id="Sources" tabindex="-1">Sources <a class="header-anchor" href="#Sources" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Sources {#Sources}&quot;">​</a></h2><ul><li><p>W. Burrus et al., <em>Fast Fourier Transforms</em>, §10.6 &quot;Generating Small FFT Kernels&quot; (eng.libretexts.org) — the four-phase summary.</p></li><li><p>M. Frigo, &quot;A Fast Fourier Transform Compiler,&quot; PLDI 1999 (fftw.org/pub/fftw/pldi99.pdf) — genfft itself.</p></li><li><p>M. Frigo and S. G. Johnson, &quot;The Design and Implementation of FFTW3,&quot; Proc. IEEE 93(2), 2005 (math.mit.edu/~stevenj/papers/FrigoJo05.pdf) — the planner, codelet composition, and SIMD.</p></li><li><p>F. Franchetti et al., &quot;SIMD Vectorization of Straight-Line FFT Code,&quot; Euro-Par 2003 (users.ece.cmu.edu/~franzf/papers/europar03.pdf) — how to vectorize straight-line FFT code.</p></li></ul>',44)])])}const u=t(r,[["render",s]]);export{g as __pageData,u as default};
